y</strong>\n\n<strong></strong>Your personal safety and wellbeing are of the utmost importance while on any trip, especially\n\n&nbsp;', 'Medical Tourism Checklist', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '10-revision-2', '', '', '2012-11-28 12:03:59', '2012-11-28 12:03:59', '', 10, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/?p=16', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES(17, 4, '2012-11-28 15:11:03', '2012-11-28 15:11:03', 'So you''re interested in the wonderful world of Medical Tourism.  Sick of the long wait times, high costs, and inferior care available to you locally?  That''s great!  But before you book a flight or hop on a train, there are a few things you''ll want to get sorted out.\n\nLike all medical procedures, medical tourism has risks, so it is important to mitigate these prior to your departure to ensure a comfortable, safe, positive, and healthy experience.  When planning your medical procedure, here are some things to take into account:\n\n<strong>Training, Accreditations, and Certifications</strong>\n\nMany clinics, regardless of their location, employ western trained physicians and clinicians.  Make sure to look into the training of the providers at the facilities that you are interested in using for your procedure so that you know what to expect upon arrival.\n\nAdditionally, specialized certifications and accreditations can be awarded to facilities from outside groups, affirming the quality and authenticity of a facility.  Organizations like <a href="http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/" target="_blank">Joint Commission </a><a href="http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/" target="_blank">International</a>, <a href="http://www.qha-international.co.uk/" target="_blank">QHA Trent</a>, the <a href="http://www.isqua.org/" target="_blank">International Society for Quality in Health Care</a> and the <a href="http://www.achs.org.au/achs-international/" target="_blank">ACHSI</a> are some of the better known accreditation organizations currently in operation and any facility which meets their standards is of the highest quality.\n\n<strong>Safety</strong>\n\n<strong></strong>Your personal safety and wellbeing are of the utmost importance while on any trip, especially with the added complication of a medical procedure.  Even though the likelihood of something happening is remote, it is better to be prepared.  Therefore, before you leave, make sure of a few things:\n\nTravel Advisories:   Check with you local government or the United States Department of State about any <a href="http://travel.state.gov/travel/cis_pa_tw/pa/pa_1766.html" target="_blank">current travel alerts</a> that may affect your trip.\n\nInsurance: Check and make sure that your personal insurance covers you while out of the country.  If it doesn''t, invest in travel insurance that will sufficiently cover you should something go wrong while you are traveling.\n\nTravel Itinerary:  Before you leave, share your itinerary with someone, just in case.  Include contact information for all of your hotels, as well as contact information for the clinic where you will have your procedure done.\n\nVaccinations:  Before traveling, talk to your current primary care provider about any vaccines you may need because of the country you are traveling to.  Vaccines should usually be given between 6-8 prior to your departure.\n\n<strong>Continuity of Care</strong>\n\n<strong></strong>When you schedule your procedure, talk with the provider about how you will receive continued care after returning to your home.  Many clinics may have partners that will be able to provide you with continuity already established.  You should also discuss the manner in which your medical records will be transmitted.  Will you be required to carry them, will they be sent to a local partner, or some other method.  It is important to have all of these questions answered\n\n&nbsp;', 'Medical Tourism Checklist', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '10-revision-3', '', '', '2012-11-28 15:11:03', '2012-11-28 15:11:03', '', 10, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/?p=17', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES(18, 4, '2012-11-28 15:24:03', '2012-11-28 15:24:03', 'So you''re interested in the wonderful world of Medical Tourism.  Sick of the long wait times, high costs, and inferior care available to you locally?  That''s great!  But before you book a flight or hop on a train, there are a few things you''ll want to get sorted out.\n\nLike all medical procedures, medical tourism has risks, so it is important to mitigate these prior to your departure to ensure a comfortable, safe, positive, and healthy experience.  When planning your medical procedure, here are some things to take into account:\n\n<strong>Training, Accreditations, and Certifications</strong>\n\nMany clinics, regardless of their location, employ western trained physicians and clinicians.  Make sure to look into the training of the providers at the facilities that you are interested in using for your procedure so that you know what to expect upon arrival.\n\nAdditionally, specialized certifications and accreditations can be awarded to facilities from outside groups, affirming the quality and authenticity of a facility.  Organizations like <a href="http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/" target="_blank">Joint Commission </a><a href="http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/" target="_blank">International</a>, <a href="http://www.qha-international.co.uk/" target="_blank">QHA Trent</a>, the <a href="http://www.isqua.org/" target="_blank">International Society for Quality in Health Care</a> and the <a href="http://www.achs.org.au/achs-international/" target="_blank">ACHSI</a> are some of the better known accreditation organizations currently in operation and any facility which meets their standards is of the highest quality.\n\n<strong>Safety</strong>\n\n<strong></strong>Your personal safety and wellbeing are of the utmost importance while on any trip, especially with the added complication of a medical procedure.  Even though the likelihood of something happening is remote, it is better to be prepared.  Therefore, before you leave, make sure of a few things:\n\nTravel Advisories:   Check with you local government or the United States Department of State about any <a href="http://travel.state.gov/travel/cis_pa_tw/pa/pa_1766.html" target="_blank">current travel alerts</a> that may affect your trip.\n\nInsurance: Check and make sure that your personal insurance covers you while out of the country.  If it doesn''t, invest in travel insurance that will sufficiently cover you should something go wrong while you are traveling.\n\nTravel Itinerary:  Before you leave, share your itinerary with someone, just in case.  Include contact information for all of your hotels, as well as contact information for the clinic where you will have your procedure done.\n\nVaccinations and Health Concerns:  Before traveling, talk to your current primary care provider about any vaccines you may need because of the country you are traveling to.  Vaccines should usually be given between 6-8 prior to your departure.  You should also talk to your primary care provider about any health issues that might affect your ability to travel or your recovery.\n\n<strong>Continuity of Care</strong>\n\n<strong></strong>When you schedule your procedure, talk with the provider about how you will receive continued care after returning to your home.  Many clinics may have partners that will be able to provide you with continuity already established.  You should also discuss the manner in which your medical records will be transmitted.  Will you be required to carry them, will they be sent to a local partner, or some other method.  It is important to have all of these questions answered prior to your departure to ensure there are no unexpected complications during your convalescence.\n\n<strong>Further Resources</strong>\n\n<strong></strong>The best way to make sure you have a good medical tourism experience is to be educated.  Below are more resources that will help you have the best experience possible.  You''re now taking the first steps into a world of healthcare opportunities.\n\n<a href="http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/yellowbook/2012/chapter-2-the-pre-travel-consultation/medical-tourism.htm" target="_blank">CDC Yellow Book Medical Tourism</a>\n\n<a href="http://www.who.int/ith/en/" target="_blank">World Health Organization - International Travel and Health</a>\n\n<a href="http://www.ama-assn.org/ama1/pub/upload/mm/31/medicaltourism.pdf" target="_blank">American Medical Association Guidelines on Medical Tourism </a>\n\n<a href="http://www.ada.org/371.aspx" target="_blank">American Dental Association Guide to Dental Care Away from Home</a>', 'Medical Tourism Checklist', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '10-revision-4', '', '', '2012-11-28 15:24:03', '2012-11-28 15:24:03', '', 10, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/?p=18', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
