es $196 million.  The remainder is a boost to ancillary services, such as hotel accommodations, food purchases, and shopping.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Medical Tourism Booming in Costa Rica', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '39-revision-4', '', '', '2012-12-11 11:20:16', '2012-12-11 11:20:16', '', 39, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/39-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES(62, 4, '2012-11-30 13:20:45', '2012-11-30 13:20:45', 'So you''re interested in the wonderful world of Medical Tourism.  Sick of the long wait times, high costs, and inferior care available to you locally?  That''s great!  But before you book a flight or hop on a train, there are a few things you''ll want to get sorted out.\r\n\r\nLike all medical procedures, medical tourism has risks, so it is important to mitigate these prior to your departure to ensure a comfortable, safe, positive, and healthy experience.  When planning your medical procedure, here are some things to take into account:\r\n\r\n<strong>Training, Accreditations, and Certifications</strong>\r\n\r\nMany clinics, regardless of their location, employ western trained physicians and clinicians.  Make sure to look into the training of the providers at the facilities that you are interested in using for your procedure so that you know what to expect upon arrival.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, specialized certifications and accreditations can be awarded to facilities from outside groups, affirming the quality and authenticity of a facility.  Organizations like <a href="http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/" target="_blank">Joint Commission </a><a href="http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/" target="_blank">International</a>, <a href="http://www.qha-international.co.uk/" target="_blank">QHA Trent</a>, the <a href="http://www.isqua.org/" target="_blank">International Society for Quality in Health Care</a> and the <a href="http://www.achs.org.au/achs-international/" target="_blank">ACHSI</a> are some of the better known accreditation organizations currently in operation and any facility which meets their standards is of the highest quality.\r\n\r\n<strong>Safety</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong></strong>Your personal safety and wellbeing are of the utmost importance while on any trip, especially with the added complication of a medical procedure.  Even though the likelihood of something happening is remote, it is better to be prepared.  Therefore, before you leave, make sure of a few things:\r\n\r\nTravel Advisories:   Check with you local government or the United States Department of State about any <a href="http://travel.state.gov/travel/cis_pa_tw/pa/pa_1766.html" target="_blank">current travel alerts</a> that may affect your trip.\r\n\r\nInsurance: Check and make sure that your personal insurance covers you while out of the country.  If it doesn''t, invest in travel insurance that will sufficiently cover you should something go wrong while you are traveling.\r\n\r\nTravel Itinerary:  Before you leave, share your itinerary with someone, just in case.  Include contact information for all of your hotels, as well as contact information for the clinic where you will have your procedure done.\r\n\r\nVaccinations and Health Concerns:  Before traveling, talk to your current primary care provider about any vaccines you may need because of the country you are traveling to.  Vaccines should usually be given between 6-8 prior to your departure.  You should also talk to your primary care provider about any health issues that might affect your ability to travel or your recovery.\r\n\r\n<strong>Continuity of Care</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong></strong>When you schedule your procedure, talk with the provider about how you will receive continued care after returning to your home.  Many clinics may have partners that will be able to provide you with continuity already established.  You should also discuss the manner in which your medical records will be transmitted.  Will you be required to carry them, will they be sent to a local partner, or some other method.  It is important to have all of these questions answered prior to your departure to ensure there are no unexpected complications during your convalescence.\r\n\r\n<strong>Further Resources</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong></strong>The best way to make sure you have a good medical tourism experience is to be educated.  Below are more resources that will help you have the best experience possible.  You''re now taking the first steps into a world of healthcare opportunities.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/yellowbook/2012/chapter-2-the-pre-travel-consultation/medical-tourism.htm" target="_blank">CDC Yellow Book Medical Tourism</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.who.int/ith/en/" target="_blank">World Health Organization - International Travel and Health</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.ama-assn.org/ama1/pub/upload/mm/31/medicaltourism.pdf" target="_blank">American Medical Association Guidelines on Medical Tourism </a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.ada.org/371.aspx" target="_blank">American Dental Association Guide to Dental Care Away from Home</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.iamat.org/index.cfm" target="_blank">The International Association of Medical Assistance to Travelers</a>', 'Medical Tourism Checklist', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '10-revision-8', '', '', '2012-11-30 13:20:45', '2012-11-30 13:20:45', '', 10, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/10-revision-8/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES(63, 4, '2012-11-30 13:20:14', '2012-11-30 13:20:14', 'A health savings account (HSA) is a medical savings account available to taxpayers in the United States who are enrolled in a high deductible health plan.  An HSA is owned by the individual, who deposits money, often matched by their employer, into their account.  This total is rolled over from year to year, allowing individuals to build the value over an extended period of time.  HSAs possess tax benefits in that they are not subject to federal income tax at the time of deposit, and if withdrawals are made for approved healthcare services, the withdrawal is tax free as well.\r\n\r\nThe benefit for people with HSAs that are interested in medical tourism is that almost all aspects of a medical tourism trip are included as approved healthcare services for procedures deemed medically necessary.  This means that your medical procedure, airfare, local travel, and accommodations while traveling are all payable, tax free, out of your HSA.\r\n\r\nSo in addition to the tremendous savings that can be found through medical tourism, the power of bundling the savings with the tax-free advantages available through an HSA make it truly a remarkable opportunity.', 'Medical Tourism and Health Savings Accounts: All Aboard!', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '14-revision-7', '', '', '2012-11-30 13:20:14', '2012-11-30 13:20:14', '', 14, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/14-revision-7/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES(69, 7, '2013-01-11 03:47:17', '2013-01-11 03:47:17', 'Starting in January, Wal-Mart will begin to allow covered employees and dependents to travel, at no personal cost, to one of six national hospitals to receive treatment for heart, spine, and transplant surgery related treatments.  Additionally, patients will receive free travel and accommodations while undergoing treatment.  Wal-Mart''s ability to work directly with hospitals to cut costs for their employees is a trend that corporations are beginning to take advantage of.\n\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="500"]<img title="PepsiCo began offering the option to travel to Baltimore to receive treatment at Johns Hopkins Medical" alt="Pepsi gettin'' busy By Bristol Motor Speedway &amp; Dragway" src="http://farm4.staticflickr.com/3077/2764687712_0859df3978.jpg" width="500" height="375" /> PepsiCo began offering the option to travel to Baltimore to receive treatment at Johns Hopkins Medical<br />Photo by <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/bristolmotorspeedway/">Bristol Motor Speedway &amp; Dragway</a>[/caption]\n\nKroger Co., grocery store giant, has partnered with several hospitals across the U.S. and offered to cover a greater portion of the cost if employees are willing to receive treatment at a partner facility.  Employees pay only 10% of the cost of a procedure if they choose to receive their treatment at one of the 19 partner hospitals, while choosing to a nearby medical center may cost them anywhere from 25% to 50% out of pocket.\n\nEarlier this year, PepsiCo began offering the option to travel to Baltimore to receive treatment at Johns Hopkins Medical.  Patients requiring treatments for cardiac problems or complex joint replacement surgeries will have their deductibles and co-insurance waived if they choose to travel for treatment.  They will also be able to have a companion accompany them, and both will travel and stay free of charge.\n\nAs healthcare costs continue to climb, traveling for healthcare will become a more and more viable option as a way to keep medical bills from skyrocketing as well.', 'Major Employers begin to take notice of Medical Tourism', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '25-autosave', '', '', '2013-01-11 03:47:17', '2013-01-11 03:47:17', '', 25, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/25-autosave/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES(71, 0, '2012-12-11 11:38:52', '2012-12-11 11:38:52', 'Both India and Dubai have recently announced provisions to make it easier for medical tourists to receive treatment in their countries.\r\n\r\nIn Dubai, medical tourists will be able to take advantage of a new ''Medical Tourist'' visa, which will allow a patient to stay in the country for up to three months.  This visa can be extended twice, for a total of up to nine consecutive months.  This move looks to unify medical tourism procedures in Dubai, and is a result of recent meetings between the Dubai Health Authority and the General Directorate of Residency and Foreigners Affairs.  The project is in its beginning stages still, and will still take some time to be fully implemented.  This first phase involves the dissemination of information to qualified hospitals on the procedures that will be required for them to apply for a medical tourism visa on behalf of an overseas patient.\r\n\r\nAt the moment, only hospitals that hold accreditation from <a href="http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/">Joint Commission Internationa</a>l (JCI), or are in the process of obtaining accreditation, will be eligible to apply for the medical tourism visas.  There are 16 hospitals that currently hold this accreditation in Dubai alone, and almost 40 in the United Arab Emirates, although the current visa agreement is only for Dubai.\r\n\r\nIn India, there has been a relaxing of the visa restrictions that have made it difficult for medical tourists to get the proper care.  In 2009, after the Mumbai terror attacks, a restriction requiring a two month gap between visits for people from certain countries was put in place.  These restrictions are now being lifted, and there is hope that medical tourists from the Persian Gulf countries will increase as a result.  The proximity of Chennai, a major medical tourism hub, and the Persian Gulf, is a big draw.\r\n\r\nAbdullah Owais, a citizen of the United Arab Emirates whose father is receiving treatment in Chennai, said, "We are happy to come here as the people are nice and the treatment is world class. This is my second visit and Chennai is only a three-hour flight from there."\r\n\r\nAlthough prior to the lifting of the restriction many procedures were done through medical visas, the new easing allows patients the ability to do a site visit prior to any procedures.  According to cardiologist Dr Ullas Pandurangi, "The easing of visa norms is a welcome move as patients can meet the doctors, go back and discuss the details with their families, and return for the procedure. Earlier, most of these discussions took place over email or through intermediaries. There is nothing like a patient visiting the doctor personally."', 'Visas Easing Access to Healthcare Abroad', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '41-revision-7', '', '', '2012-12-11 11:38:52', '2012-12-11 11:38:52', '', 41, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/41-revision-7/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
