 offered their own private room and face-to-face personal interaction with their doctor or surgeon. Hospitals and clinics are equipped with up-to-date technology, well-trained doctors and ''on-hand'' medical staff to cater to all types of medical tourists.\r\n\r\nThe most common treatments sought in Mexico  by medical tourists include:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">Cosmetic surgery</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">Dentistry</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">Aesthetic procedures (Botox, etc)</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">Hip replacement</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">Knee replacement</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">Orthopedic surgery</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">Bariatric surgery</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">Eye surgery</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">Cardiac surgery</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAs of December 2012, there were 12 JCI Joint Commission International (JCI) Accredited medical centers in Mexico.\r\n\r\n(<a href="http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/JCI-Accredited-Organizations/">http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/JCI-Accredited-Organizations/</a>)\r\n\r\nIn addition, Mexico has the third highest number of surgeons affiliated to the International Society of Aesthetic Plastic Surgery (ISAPS) after United States and Brazil.', 'Mexico Remains the Most Popular Medical Tourism Destination for U.S.', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '91-revision-8', '', '', '2013-01-10 11:53:40', '2013-01-10 11:53:40', '', 91, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/91-revision-8/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES(177, 7, '2012-12-17 05:02:31', '2012-12-17 05:02:31', 'Thirty eight percent of Americans would consider traveling abroad to undergo medical procedures at a lower cost, says recent survey on behalf of Reuters News conducted by independent market research company Ipsos.\r\n\r\nThe poll of 18,731 adults in 24 countries (November 2011) found other developed nations such as Italy (66%) along with Germany (48%) and Canada (41%) were open to the idea.\r\n\r\n"It is a reflection that the medical profession is no longer protected from globalization," Nicolas Boyon, senior vice president of Ipsos Public Affairs, told Reuters.\r\n\r\nAdditional Findings:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Young adults more open to medical tourism</li>\r\n	<li>Common treatments - dental, fertility, cosmetic surgery</li>\r\n	<li>Indians most open to medical tourism, Japanese least</li>\r\n	<li>Men (19%) were slightly more likely than women (17%)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe survey included respondents from Argentina, Australia, Belgium, Brazil, Canada, China, France, Germany, Great Britain, Hungary, India, Indonesia, Italy, Japan, Mexico, Poland, Russia, Saudi Arabia, South Africa, South Korea, Spain, Sweden, Turkey and the United States.\r\n\r\n<b><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Links</span></b>\r\n\r\nReuters Article:  <a href="http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/11/13/us-medicaltourism-idUSBRE8AC0Q220121113">http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/11/13/us-medicaltourism-idUSBRE8AC0Q220121113</a>\r\n\r\nIpsos Report Summary:   <a href="http://www.ipsos-na.com/news-polls/pressrelease.aspx?id=5886">http://www.ipsos-na.com/news-polls/pressrelease.aspx?id=5886</a>', 'Is Medical Profession No Longer Safe From Globalization? - One in Three Open to Traveling for Medical Treatment, Poll Finds ', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '85-revision-6', '', '', '2012-12-17 05:02:31', '2012-12-17 05:02:31', '', 85, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/85-revision-6/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
