s discover prices are about half of what U.S. clinics charge.  While Singapore clinics and hospitals generally provide more opulent pre/post patient care than one would expect to receive from a U.S. provider.</div>', 'Singapore Leading the Way For Medical Tourism in Asia and the World', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '110-revision-15', '', '', '2013-01-10 16:59:06', '2013-01-10 16:59:06', '', 110, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/110-revision-15/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES(194, 7, '2013-01-10 15:38:17', '2013-01-10 15:38:17', 'A health savings account (HSA) is a medical savings account available to taxpayers in the United States who are enrolled in a high deductible health plan.  An HSA is owned by the individual, who deposits money, often matched by their employer, into their account.  This total is rolled over from year to year, allowing individuals to build the value over an extended period of time.  HSAs possess tax benefits in that they are not subject to federal income tax at the time of deposit, and if withdrawals are made for approved healthcare services, the withdrawal is tax free as well.\r\n\r\nThe benefit for people with HSAs that are interested in medical tourism is that almost all aspects of a medical tourism trip are included as approved healthcare services for procedures deemed medically necessary.  This means that your medical procedure, airfare, local travel, and accommodations while traveling are all payable, tax free, out of your HSA.\r\n\r\nSo in addition to the tremendous savings that can be found through medical tourism, the power of bundling the savings with the tax-free advantages available through an HSA make it truly a remarkable opportunity.', 'Medical Tourism and Health Savings Accounts: All Aboard!', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '14-revision-10', '', '', '2013-01-10 15:38:17', '2013-01-10 15:38:17', '', 14, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/14-revision-10/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES(195, 7, '2013-01-10 15:38:53', '2013-01-10 15:38:53', 'So you''re interested in the wonderful world of Medical Tourism.  Sick of the long wait times, high costs, and inferior care available to you locally?  That''s great!  But before you book a flight or hop on a train, there are a few things you''ll want to get sorted out.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="aligncenter" width="500"]<img alt="First Class Health Care in Panama" src="http://farm3.staticflickr.com/2149/2234741663_2d1ef65cf2.jpg" width="500" height="365" /> Photo by <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/23065375@N05/">ThinkPanama</a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nLike all medical procedures, medical tourism has risks, so it is important to mitigate these prior to your departure to ensure a comfortable, safe, positive, and healthy experience.  When planning your medical procedure, here are some things to take into account:\r\n\r\n<strong>Training, Accreditations, and Certifications</strong>\r\n\r\nMany clinics, regardless of their location, employ western trained physicians and clinicians.  Make sure to look into the training of the providers at the facilities that you are interested in using for your procedure so that you know what to expect upon arrival.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, specialized certifications and accreditations can be awarded to facilities from outside groups, affirming the quality and authenticity of a facility.  Organizations like <a href="http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/" target="_blank">Joint Commission </a><a href="http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/" target="_blank">International</a>, <a href="http://www.qha-international.co.uk/" target="_blank">QHA Trent</a>, the <a href="http://www.isqua.org/" target="_blank">International Society for Quality in Health Care</a> and the <a href="http://www.achs.org.au/achs-international/" target="_blank">ACHSI</a> are some of the better known accreditation organizations currently in operation and any facility which meets their standards is of the highest quality.\r\n\r\n<strong>Safety</strong>\r\n\r\nYour personal safety and wellbeing are of the utmost importance while on any trip, especially with the added complication of a medical procedure.  Even though the likelihood of something happening is remote, it is better to be prepared.  Therefore, before you leave, make sure of a few things:\r\n\r\nTravel Advisories:   Check with you local government or the United States Department of State about any <a href="http://travel.state.gov/travel/cis_pa_tw/pa/pa_1766.html" target="_blank">current travel alerts</a> that may affect your trip.\r\n\r\nInsurance: Check and make sure that your personal insurance covers you while out of the country.  If it doesn''t, invest in travel insurance that will sufficiently cover you should something go wrong while you are traveling.\r\n\r\nTravel Itinerary:  Before you leave, share your itinerary with someone, just in case.  Include contact information for all of your hotels, as well as contact information for the clinic where you will have your procedure done.\r\n\r\nVaccinations and Health Concerns:  Before traveling, talk to your current primary care provider about any vaccines you may need because of the country you are traveling to.  Vaccines should usually be given between 6-8 prior to your departure.  You should also talk to your primary care provider about any health issues that might affect your ability to travel or your recovery.\r\n\r\n<strong>Continuity of Care</strong>\r\n\r\nWhen you schedule your procedure, talk with the provider about how you will receive continued care after returning to your home.  Many clinics may have partners that will be able to provide you with continuity already established.  You should also discuss the manner in which your medical records will be transmitted.  Will you be required to carry them, will they be sent to a local partner, or some other method.  It is important to have all of these questions answered prior to your departure to ensure there are no unexpected complications during your convalescence.\r\n\r\n<strong>Further Resources</strong>\r\n\r\nThe best way to make sure you have a good medical tourism experience is to be educated.  Below are more resources that will help you have the best experience possible.  You''re now taking the first steps into a world of healthcare opportunities.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/yellowbook/2012/chapter-2-the-pre-travel-consultation/medical-tourism.htm" target="_blank">CDC Yellow Book Medical Tourism</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.who.int/ith/en/" target="_blank">World Health Organization - International Travel and Health</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.ama-assn.org/ama1/pub/upload/mm/31/medicaltourism.pdf" target="_blank">American Medical Association Guidelines on Medical Tourism </a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.ada.org/371.aspx" target="_blank">American Dental Association Guide to Dental Care Away from Home</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.iamat.org/index.cfm" target="_blank">The International Association of Medical Assistance to Travelers</a>', 'Medical Tourism Checklist', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '10-revision-13', '', '', '2013-01-10 15:38:53', '2013-01-10 15:38:53', '', 10, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/10-revision-13/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES(196, 7, '2013-01-10 15:38:36', '2013-01-10 15:38:36', 'According to <a href="http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/11/27/uk-costarica-tourism-idUSLNE8AQ01720121127">Reuters</a>, medical tourism in Costa Rica is up 33% in the last two years, and is now competing with other destinations like Mexico, India, Brazil, and Panama for the top spot for medical tourism.  It is being helped by its stable government and its proximity to the United States and Canada, which supply the majority of Costa Rica''s medical tourists.\r\n\r\nMany, including Alberta, Canada''s Marlene Trithardt, are coming for the potential savings.  Ms. Trithardt, who needed a tooth replaced, but was unable to afford the $10,000 it would cost in Alberta, was able to have the same procedure in Costa Rica for only $4,000.  This cost includes airfare, treatment, hotel stay, and meals for two weeks.\r\n\r\n“I chose to come here," Ms. Trithardt told Reuters, "because I find in Alberta the prices are about 80 percent higher than in Costa Rica."\r\n\r\nAccording to statistics provided by the Costa Rica tourism institute ICT, there were about 40,000 medical tourists traveling to Costa Rica in 2011.  This is up from 36,000 in 2010, and 30,000 in 2009.  Massimo Manzi, director of Promed, the council for international promotion of medicine in Costa Rica, estimates that 15,000 people, or almost 40% of those traveling to Costa Rica for medical tourism, do so because they are interested in more affordable dental care.  Mr. Manzi stated that the medical tourism industry provides $280 million boost to the Costa Rican economy, of which health care comprises $196 million.  The remainder is a boost to ancillary services, such as hotel accommodations, food purchases, and shopping.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Medical Tourism Booming in Costa Rica', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '39-revision-7', '', '', '2013-01-10 15:38:36', '2013-01-10 15:38:36', '', 39, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/39-revision-7/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES(197, 7, '2012-12-12 12:59:04', '2012-12-12 12:59:04', 'Both India and Dubai have recently announced provisions to make it easier for medical tourists to receive treatment in their countries.\r\n\r\nIn Dubai, medical tourists will be able to take advantage of a new ''Medical Tourist'' visa, which will allow a patient to stay in the country for up to three months.  This visa can be extended twice, for a total of up to nine consecutive months.  This move looks to unify medical tourism procedures in Dubai, and is a result of recent meetings between the Dubai Health Authority and the General Directorate of Residency and Foreigners Affairs.  The project is in its beginning stages still, and will still take some time to be fully implemented.  This first phase involves the dissemination of information to qualified hospitals on the procedures that will be required for them to apply for a medical tourism visa on behalf of an overseas patient.\r\n\r\nAt the moment, only hospitals that hold accreditation from <a href="http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/">Joint Commission Internationa</a>l (JCI), or are in the process of obtaining accreditation, will be eligible to apply for the medical tourism visas.  There are 16 hospitals that currently hold this accreditation in Dubai alone, and almost 40 in the United Arab Emirates, although the current visa agreement is only for Dubai.\r\n\r\nIn India, there has been a relaxing of the visa restrictions that have made it difficult for medical tourists to get the proper care.  In 2009, after the Mumbai terror attacks, a restriction requiring a two month gap between visits for people from certain countries was put in place.  These restrictions are now being lifted, and there is hope that medical tourists from the Persian Gulf countries will increase as a result.  The proximity of Chennai, a major medical tourism hub, and the Persian Gulf, is a big draw.\r\n\r\nAbdullah Owais, a citizen of the United Arab Emirates whose father is receiving treatment in Chennai, said, "We are happy to come here as the people are nice and the treatment is world class. This is my second visit and Chennai is only a three-hour flight from there."\r\n\r\nAlthough prior to the lifting of the restriction many procedures were done through medical visas, the new easing allows patients the ability to do a site visit prior to any procedures.  According to cardiologist Dr Ullas Pandurangi, "The easing of visa norms is a welcome move as patients can meet the doctors, go back and discuss the details with their families, and return for the procedure. Earlier, most of these discussions took place over email or through intermediaries. There is nothing like a patient visiting the doctor personally."', 'Visas Easing Access to Healthcare Abroad', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '41-revision-8', '', '', '2012-12-12 12:59:04', '2012-12-12 12:59:04', '', 41, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/41-revision-8/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES(198, 7, '2013-01-10 15:39:30', '2013-01-10 15:39:30', '<p><strong>Medical What?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Medical Tourism is, at its most basic, the process of traveling outside of a patient''s home region for medical care.  Usually it involves traveling internationally, but this is not required. Traditionally, medical tourism took place when individuals would travel from a lesser-developed country to receive treatment that was not available in their region.  But in the recent past there has been a growing trend of people traveling from well-developed nations to other countries for medical procedures.</p>\r\n<p>[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="500"]<img class=" " alt="Beach umbrella at sunset - Antigua, Mar 2010" src="http://farm5.staticflickr.com/4037/4435260688_9e4a789d7f.jpg" width="500" height="333" /> Beach umbrella at sunset - Antigua<br />Photo by <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/yourdon/4435260688/">Ed Yourdon</a>[/caption]</p>\r\n<p><strong>Why would someone do that?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Procedure Availability:  There are a number of reasons that an individual may travel for healthcare.  The first reason, as stated above, is that they want or require a procedure that is not available or permitted where they live.  This may be a safe, cutting edge procedure that has not been approved yet by the local medical governing body.  For example, laparascopic banding (lap band surgery) was not approved by the FDA as a treatment until 2001 while Mexico had been performing the procedure since the 1990s.  So you can see how a safe procedure, that eventually was approved by the local governing body, would have been available prior to that time through medical tourism.</p>\r\n<p>Cost Benefits:  Another reason a patient may make use of medical tourism is for the cost saving benefits.  A procedure that costs $50,000 in the United States may be done for under $10,000.  So for an uninsured or under-insured patient the savings, even with travel and accommodations, can be substantial.  Additionally, even fully insured individuals will find that there are many elective procedures that are simply not covered under insurance, and medical tourism will allow these patients to be able to get the procedure they want at an affordable price.</p>\r\n<p>Reduced Waiting Time:  A third reason that someone might choose medical tourism is to gain access to healthcare more rapidly than in their home country.  Many countries, particularly those with nationalized healthcare, can have substantial waiting times for non life-threatening procedures, sometimes up to and exceeding a year.  Sometimes these conditions, while not life-threatening, can seriously degrade one''s quality of life.  In this case, having the ability to go almost immediately and have the problem attended to, rather than suffer for a long period of time, becomes a very attractive option.</p>\r\n<p>Best-of-the-Best:  Sometimes a procedure is available in your home region, but the best doctor in the world isn''t.  For certain patients, having the procedure done by the best possible doctors available is the only acceptable option.  In this case, medical tourism provides them access to that provider no matter where they are in the world.</p>\r\n<p>Discretion:  For some patients, they don''t want the whole world to know that they have had a certain procedure, for whatever reason.  Combining a trip with a medical procedure allows a patient to maintain a certain level of discretion and be able to recover away from the stress and daily grind of their home life.  Imagine someone going away for two weeks and coming back looking ten years younger, they claim it''s just the fresh air and sea breeze, and no one is any the wiser...</p>\r\n<p>Combination Vacation:  For many procedures, the recovery time is minimal, if any is required at all.  These procedures make great excuses to make a vacation out of your medical tour.  A patient can make plans to have their procedure at either the beginning, or end of their trip, and spend the rest of the time on vacation, enjoying the culture and attractions or a new place, while still receiving that important medical procedure.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Is Medical Tourism Right for Me?</strong></p>\r\n<p>We think that a huge portion of patients could find a use for medical tourism in their lives.  While it won''t be a good fit for all patients, or all procedures, the opportunity to receive better quality care, at a lower price, in an amazing location is simply too good to pass up if the opportunity presents itself!  So just think how a world of healthcare options could improve your life!</p>\r\n', 'What is Medical Tourism?  And Why On Earth Would I be Interested In It?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '12-revision-11', '', '', '2013-01-10 15:39:30', '2013-01-10 15:39:30', '', 12, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/12-revision-11/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES(199, 7, '2013-01-10 15:39:12', '2013-01-10 15:39:12', 'Starting in January, Wal-Mart will begin to allow covered employees and dependents to travel, at no personal cost, to one of six national hospitals to receive treatment for heart, spine, and transplant surgery related treatments.  Additionally, patients will receive free travel and accommodations while undergoing treatment.  Wal-Mart''s ability to work directly with hospitals to cut costs for their employees is a trend that corporations are beginning to take advantage of.\r\n\r\nKroger Co., grocery store giant, has partnered with several hospitals across the U.S. and offered to cover a greater portion of the cost if employees are willing to receive treatment at a partner facility.  Employees pay only 10% of the cost of a procedure if they choose to receive their treatment at one of the 19 partner hospitals, while choosing to a nearby medical center may cost them anywhere from 25% to 50% out of pocket.\r\n\r\nEarlier this year, PepsiCo began offering the option to travel to Baltimore to receive treatment at Johns Hopkins Medical.  Patients requiring treatments for cardiac problems or complex joint replacement surgeries will have their deductibles and co-insurance waived if they choose to travel for treatment.  They will also be able to have a companion accompany them, and both will travel and stay free of charge.\r\n\r\nAs healthcare costs continue to climb, traveling for healthcare will become a more and more viable option as a way to keep medical bills from skyrocketing as well.', 'Major Employers begin to take notice of Medical Tourism', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '25-revision-7', '', '', '2013-01-10 15:39:12', '2013-01-10 15:39:12', '', 25, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/25-revision-7/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES(208, 7, '2013-01-14 01:44:28', '2013-01-14 01:44:28', '', 'healthcareabroad.com thailand', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'healthcareabroad-com-thailand', '', '', '2013-01-14 01:44:28', '2013-01-14 01:44:28', '', 0, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/healthcareabroad.com-thailand.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES(213, 4, '2013-01-10 15:39:43', '2013-01-10 15:39:43', 'Robotics are increasingly being used in modern medicine, and in the Indian city of Bangalore, they are being used to enable doctors to perform increasingly precise procedures and the result is an improved image in the world of medical tourism.  An article in DNA India tells the tale of Anjana, who developed a tumor in her kidney.  Traditionally, the procedure called for would be the removal of the kidney, but in Anjana''s case, she wanted to preserve the kidney, so she traveled to Bangalore to receive a procedure called robot-assisted Partial Nephrectomy.  In this procedure, the doctor is assisted by an advanced robotic system, allowing for the excision of only the tumor, and sparing the kidney.  After surgery, Anjana only had to stay three days in hospital, and was able to return to work within two weeks.  Procedures like this have seen Bangalore''s standing as a medical tourism destination rise as patients from the Middle East, Africa, Australia, The Netherlands, Denmark, Russia and Sri Lanka travel to Bangalore to take advantage of this cutting edge technology.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter" alt="Robot-Assisted Surgery adding to Bangalore’s allure as a Medical Tourism Destination - HealthcareAbroad.com" src="http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/7341200278_7f752d345a.jpg" width="500" height="333" /></p>\r\nIn addition to the field of urology, the ability for robotic assisted surgery in the field of gynecology is also promising.  According to Dr. Gayarthi Karthik, consultant gynecologist at Bangalore''s <a href="http://www.manipalhospitals.com/">Manipal Hospital</a>, "“The robot can be used in removal of fibroids, removal of uterus, hysterectomy, recanalisation of fallopian tubes in patients with blocked tubes or when sterilisation is to be reversed, endometriosis surgery and surgery for cervical and uterine cancers.”  Most gynecological procedures can be assisted-by robots, and it is the opinion of Dr. Karthik that the advances in this field and the availability in Bangalore have boosted Bangalore''s image as a medical tourism destination.\r\n\r\nA final field that is benefitting from the advances in robotics is in cancer treatment.  The robotic assistance allows for much more accurate and targeted application of the radiation treatment, affecting less surrounding tissue.  As Dr. Sridhar P S, consulting radiation oncologist at Healthcare Global, puts it, "Earlier, we faced the problem where we did not achieve accurate radiation. So, if there is a tumor in the lungs, radiation would affect the surrounding areas. However, with the help of robotic radiation, there is little damage done to the surrounding areas."\r\n\r\nThe benefits from a medical tourism perspective are great.  Not only the advancements in procedures available, and the quality of these procedures, but the increased accuracy allows for a smaller surgical site, which leads to reduced recovery times, and more time not stuck in a hospital.  Dr N. K. Venkataramana, vice-chairman and chief neurosurgeon of BGS Global Hospitals said, “Surgeons are increasingly resorting to minimally invasive surgeries wherever possible. The advantages of this technology are minimal damage to tissue and less invasiveness, lesser hospital stay, speedy ambulation of patient, less pain and cosmetically aesthetic with a smaller scar. Robotics will definitely help to achieve these goals with much more precision."', 'Robot-Assisted Surgery adding to Bangalore''s allure as a Medical Tourism Destination', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '131-revision-24', '', '', '2013-01-10 15:39:43', '2013-01-10 15:39:43', '', 131, 'http://www.healthcareabroad.com/blog/131-revision-24/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
